Here's a look at some of the alternatives:@#%^&*14
SHORT-TERM MUNICIPALS:@#%^&*14
Investors with a heavy tax load should take out their calculators.@#%^&*14
Yields on municipal bonds can be higher than after-tax yields on CDs for maturities of perhaps one to five years.@#%^&*15
That's because municipal-bond interest is exempt from federal income tax@#%^&*16
-- and from state and local taxes too, for in-state investors.@#%^&*16
For an investor@#%^&*17
paying tax at a 33% rate,@#%^&*17
a seemingly puny 6% yield on a one-year muni is equivalent to a taxable 9%.@#%^&*17
Rates approach 6.5% on five-year municipals.@#%^&*18
Some of the more cautious CD holders might like "pre-refunded" municipals.@#%^&*19
These securities get top credit ratings@#%^&*20
because the issuers have put aside U.S. bonds@#%^&*20
that will be sold@#%^&*20
to pay off holders@#%^&*20
when the municipals are retired.@#%^&*20
"It's a no-brainer:@#%^&*21
You don't have to worry about diversification;@#%^&*21
you don't have to worry about quality,"@#%^&*21
says Steven J. Hueglin, executive vice president of the New York bond firm of Gabriele, Hueglin & Cashman Inc.@#%^&*21
Consider a "laddered" bond portfolio, with issues@#%^&*22
maturing in, say, 1992, 1993 and 1994,@#%^&*22
advises Malcolm A. Makin, a Westerly, R.I., financial planner.@#%^&*22
