BOND FUNDS:@#%^&*24
Bond mutual funds offer diversification@#%^&*24
and are easy to buy and sell.@#%^&*24
That makes them a reasonable option for investors@#%^&*25
who will accept some risk of price fluctuation@#%^&*25
in order to make a bet@#%^&*25
that interest rates will decline over the next year or so.@#%^&*25
Buyers can look forward to double-digit annual returns@#%^&*26
if they are right.@#%^&*26
But they will have disappointing returns or even losses@#%^&*27
if interest rates rise instead.@#%^&*27
Bond resale prices, and thus fund share prices, move in the opposite direction from rates.@#%^&*28
The price movements get bigger@#%^&*29
as the maturity of the securities lengthens.@#%^&*29
Consider, for instance, two bond funds from Vanguard Group of Investment Cos.@#%^&*30
that were both yielding 8.6% on a recent day.@#%^&*31
The Short Term Bond Fund, with an average maturity of 2 1/2 years, would deliver a total return for one year of about 10.6%@#%^&*32
if rates drop one percentage point@#%^&*32
and a one-year return of about 6.6%@#%^&*32
if rates rise by the same amount.@#%^&*32
But, in the same circumstances, the returns would be a more extreme 14.6% and 2.6% for the Vanguard Bond Market Fund, with its 12 1/2-year average maturity.@#%^&*33
"You get equity-like returns" from bonds@#%^&*34
if you guess right on rates,@#%^&*34
says James E. Wilson, a Columbia, S.C., planner.@#%^&*34
If interest rates don't change,@#%^&*35
bond fund investors' returns will be about equal to the funds' current yields.@#%^&*35
